default&#xa0;default3.1
default              
defaultThis submission illustrates the grave consequences of the proposal by providing an in depth analysis of the impact of a
default judicial review brought by the Howard League for Penal Reform in 2002, 
defaultThe Queen (on the 
defaultApplication of the Howard League) v Secretary of State for the Home Department and the Department of Health
default [2003] 1 FLR 484
default [‘The 
defaultChildren Act
default case’]
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default              
defaultThe proposed restriction on standing would have prevented the Howard League for Penal reform 
defaultfrom b
defaultringing this case.
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default              
defaultAs 
defaultset out below
default, there is considerable evidence that the impact of this case was wide-ranging and important. 
defaultWhere there is a genuine public interest, it can only be right and proper 
defaultin
default a civil
default society that
default organisations have the o
defaultpportunity to bring these pivotal cases to court. The judiciary must be allowed to exercise their constitutional function to provide 
defaultjudicial scrutiny of important issues brought to the
defaultir att
defaultention by organisations as well as individuals.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe issues in t
defaulthe 
defaultChildren Act 
defaultcase
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default              
defaultIn this case, the Howard League for Penal reformdefault challenge
defaultd
default the legality of the Secretary of State's policy guidance on the treatment of children
default under 18 years of age held in Young Offender I
defaultnstitutions. The Secretary of State 
defaulthad asserted in Prison Service Order No 4950
default, which governed the regime for children detained in Young Offenders’ Institutions,
default that the
default Children Act 1989 
defaultdid not apply in respect of such children. 
defaultWe argued that 
defaultpolicy guidance was wrong in law. The main 
defaultissues for determination were the extent to which the 1989 Act applied to children in 
defaultY
defaultoung 
defaultO
defaultffender
defaults’
default 
defaultI
defaultnstitutions, the legality of the Secretary of State's treatment of juveniles in 
defaultYoung Offender I
defaultnstitutions 
defaultand whether child protection work in 
defaultY
defaultoung 
defaultO
defaultffender
defaults’
default 
defaultI
defaultnstitutions should be led by local authorities. 
default&#xa0;
default3.5
default              
defaultThe judicial review was successful.  The Court held 
defaultthat although the 
default1989 Act did not confer or impose any powers or obligations on the Secretary of State or the Prison Service, the duties o
defaultwed by a local authority to juveniles under s
defaultection 
default17
default (duties towards ‘children in need’)
default and s
defaultection 
default47
default (duties towards children at risk of serious harm)
default of the Act did not cease merely because a juvenile was in a young offender institution. However, a local authority's powers and duties under the Act took effect and operated subject to the necessary requirements of imprisonment.
default  
default&#xa0;
default3.6
default              
defaultThis meant that chi
defaultldren in prison were not offenders to be treated differently from children in the community
default,
default but children who were entitled as a matter of law to full rights under the Children Act 1989.  This meant that if they were in need and appeared to the local autho
defaultrity to require help to prevent the any further impairment to their health and development, the local authority was required to provide it under s
defaultection 
default17 of the Children Act 1989.  Similarly, if there was reason to believe a child was at risk of serious 
defaultharm, the local authority where the prison was based was required as a matter
default of law to investigate this.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default4. default              defaultImpact of the case on policy, practice and children’s livesdefault&#xa0;
default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
