default4.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultrelationship between 
defaultthese changes 
defaultand the 
defaultChildren Act
default case 
defaultare outlined on the Ministry of J
defaultustice’s website as follows:
default“On 29 November 2002, Mr Justice Munby judged that the Children Act (1989) should apply to children detained in young offender institutions (YOIs), that duties owed by local authorities continue to be owed to children in YOIs a
defaultnd that human rights legislation, particularly the Human Rights Act (1998), applies to children in custodial facilities.
default“
defaultThe report, 
defaultThe Application of the Children Act (1989) to Children in Young Offender Institutions
default&#xa0;
defaultexamines the application of the 
defaultChildren Act to children in custody, in light of this judgement.
default“
defaultThe
default&#xa0;
defaultNational Children’s Bureau
default 
default(NCB) has produced a document entitled
default&#xa0;
defaultTell them not to forget about us
default a guide to practice with looked-after children in custody. Aimed primarily at children’s services authorities, this guide will also be of use and in
defaultterest to secure estate and YOT staff as it outlines roles and responsibilities for all partnership agencies.
default“
defaultThe revised
default&#xa0;
defaultWorking Together
default [guidance] provides further detail on how secure establishments and local authorities should discharge their statutory duties. Importantly, agreed procedures must be in place between secure establishments and those local a
defaultuthorities (in particular the LSCB) that have secure establishments in their area, outlining how to deal with and undertake child in need assessments and child protection allegations. LSCBs will have oversight of the safeguarding arrangements within secure
default settings in their area.
default“
defaultIn discharging these duties, local authority children’s social care services should consider seconding social workers to work in secure establishments and establish effective links with a child or young person’s home local authori
defaultty. The home local authority and YOT have continuing responsibilities to children and young people in custody.
default“
defaultThe Working Together document includes further details for secure providers on how to effectively work with young people who are looked after as
default well as arrangements for successful transitions between custodial establishments and community services.”
default4.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt should be noted that Working Together is statutory guidance that must be followed in relation to child protection issues.
default 
defaultThese changes represented a sea change in the way in which children in prison were considered.  In 
defaulta report
default by the Association of Directors of Social Services, the Local Government Association and the Youth Justice Board,  
defaultThe Application of the Children 
defaultAct (1989) to Children in Young Offender Institutions
